    "\n",

     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "a:\n",
      " [[0 1 2]\n",
      " [3 4 5]\n",
      " [6 7 8]]\n",
      "b:\n",
      " [[1 2 3]\n",
      " [4 5 6]\n",
      " [7 8 9]]\n",
      "a + b:\n",
      " [[ 1  3  5]\n",
      " [ 7  9 11]\n",
      " [13 15 17]]\n",
      "a * b:\n",
      " [[ 0  2  6]\n",
      " [12 20 30]\n",
      " [42 56 72]]\n",
      "a dot b:\n",
      " [[ 18  21  24]\n",
      " [ 54  66  78]\n",
      " [ 90 111 132]]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "a = np.reshape(np.arange(9),(3,3))\n",
    "b = np.reshape(np.arange(1,10),(3,3))\n",
    "print(\"a:\\n\",a)\n",
    "print(\"b:\\n\",b)\n",
    "print(\"a + b:\\n\",a+b)\n",
    "print(\"a * b:\\n\",a*b)\n",
    "print(\"a dot b:\\n\",np.dot(a,b))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see that the normal arithmetical operators `+` and `*` operate element by element, so that the result is `a[i,j] + b[i,j]` or `a[i,j] * b[i,j]` (in matrix terms, we have $a_{ij} + b_{ij}$).  `np.dot` performs a matrix multiply (you can also write `a.dot(b)` but I personally find that a little confusing)."
   ]
  },

    "### Question 5"

     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "v:\n",
      " [1 2 3]\n",
      "w:\n",
      " [2 3 4]\n",
      "Numpy outer product:\n",
      " [[ 2  3  4]\n",
      " [ 4  6  8]\n",
      " [ 6  9 12]]\n",
      "Simple vT * w\n",
      " [[ 2  3  4]\n",
      " [ 4  6  8]\n",

      " [ 2  6 12]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "v = np.arange(1,4)\n",
    "w = np.arange(2,5)\n",
    "print(\"v:\\n\",v)\n",
    "print(\"w:\\n\",w)\n",
    "print(\"Numpy outer product:\\n\",np.outer(v,w))\n",
    "print(\"Simple vT * w\\n\",np.reshape(v,(3,1))*w)\n",
    "print(\"Simple v * w\\n\",v*w)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The outer product of two vectors gives a matrix: $A_{ij} = v_i w_j$.  When a Numpy operator is asked to operate on arrays of different shapes, it performs an operation called broadcasting so that the arrays have the same shape.  The simple multiplication is, as before, an element-wise operation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Loops and control\n",
    "\n",
    "### Questions 1 & 2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "delta = 0.005\n",
    "lim = [-2,0.6,-1.2,1.2]\n",
    "x = np.arange(lim[0],lim[1]+delta,delta)\n",
    "y = np.arange(lim[2],lim[3]+delta,delta)\n",
    "n_samp_x = len(x)\n",
    "n_samp_y = len(y)\n",
    "res = np.zeros((n_samp_y,n_samp_x))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Questions 3 & 4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "for i, x0 in enumerate(x):\n",
    "    for j, y0 in enumerate(y):\n",
    "        z = [0,0]\n",
    "        iters = 0\n",
    "        z = [z[0]*z[0]-z[1]*z[1]+x0,2*z[0]*z[1]+y0]\n",
    "        mag = z[0]*z[0]+z[1]*z[1]\n",
    "        while (mag<4.0) and (iters<70):\n",
    "            z = [z[0]*z[0]-z[1]*z[1]+x0,2*z[0]*z[1]+y0]\n",
    "            mag = z[0]*z[0]+z[1]*z[1]\n",
    "            iters += 1\n",
    "        res[j,i]=1-np.sqrt(iters/70)"
   ]
  },

    "## 5. Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "### Question 1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def split_array_into_n(array,n):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Split array into n sub-arrays and return as list\"\"\"\n",
    "    b = []\n",
    "    for i in range(n):\n",
    "        b.append(array[i::n])\n",
    "    return b"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def interleave_n_arrays(array_list,n):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Interleave n arrays in input (array_list) into one array\"\"\"\n",
    "    length = sum([len(input[i]) for i in range(n)])\n",
    "    out = np.zeros(length)\n",
    "    for i in range(n):\n",
    "        out[i::n] = input[i]\n",
    "    return out"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Question 3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def mandelbrot_iteration(x0,y0):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Perform Mandelbrot iteration on number (x0+iy0) and return iterations\"\"\"\n",
    "    z = [0,0]\n",
    "    iters = 0\n",
    "    z = [z[0]*z[0]-z[1]*z[1]+x0,2*z[0]*z[1]+y0]\n",
    "    mag = z[0]*z[0]+z[1]*z[1]\n",
    "    while (mag<4.0) and (iters<70):\n",
    "        z = [z[0]*z[0]-z[1]*z[1]+x0,2*z[0]*z[1]+y0]\n",
    "        mag = z[0]*z[0]+z[1]*z[1]\n",
    "        iters += 1\n",
    "    return iters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "res_fun = np.zeros((n_samp_y,n_samp_x))\n",
    "for i, x0 in enumerate(x):\n",
    "    for j, y0 in enumerate(y):\n",
    "        res_fun[j,i]=1-np.sqrt(mandelbrot_iteration(x0,y0)/70)"
   ]
